      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2016_Solutions_2016s_page_002_4",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A4 The minimum number of tiles is mn. To see that this many are required, label the squares (i, j) with 1 ≤ i ≤ 2m - 1 and 1 ≤ j < 2n - 1, and for each square with i, j both odd, color the square red; then no tile can cover more than one red square, and there are mn red squares.",
        "bbox": [
          0.10338346628507948,
          0.19040697673751888,
          0.490601508319854,
          0.2601744179575801
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2016_Solutions_2016s_page_002_5",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "It remains to show that we can cover any (2m - 1) x (2n - 1) rectangle with mn tiles when m,n ≥ 4. First note that we can tile any 2 x (2k - 1) rectangle with k ≥ 3 by k tiles: one of the first type, then k - 2 of the second type, and finally one of the first type. Thus if we can cover a 7 x 7 square with 16 tiles, then we can do the general (2m - 1) × (2n - 1) rectangle, by decomposing this rectangle into a 7 x 7 square in the lower left corner, along with m - 4 (2 x 7) rectangles to the right of the square, and n - 4 ((2m - 1) × 2) rectangles above, and tiling each of these rectangles separately, for a total of 16 + 4(m -4) + m(n- 4) = mn tiles.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12593986446362662,
          0.26736111101009885,
          0.49060151109241035,
          0.4389880953960464
        ],
        "order": 9
      }
    ]
  },
